# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: financial-fix-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In finance, an **electronic trading platform**, also known as an **online trading platform**, is a computer software program that can be used to place orders for financial products over a network with a financial intermediary.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Various financial products can be traded by the trading platform, over a communication network with a financial intermediary or directly between the participants or members of the trading platform.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] This includes products such as stocks, bonds, currencies, commodities, derivatives and others, with a financial intermediary such as brokers, market makers, investment banks or stock exchanges.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Such platforms allow electronic trading to be carried out by users from any location and are in contrast to traditional floor trading using open outcry and telephone-based trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Sometimes the term trading platform is also used in reference to the trading software alone.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms typically stream live market prices on which users can trade and may provide additional trading tools, such as charting packages, news feeds and account management functions.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Some platforms have been specifically designed to allow individuals to gain access to financial markets that could formerly only be accessed by specialist trading firms using direct market access.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] They may also be designed to automatically trade specific strategies based on technical analysis or to do high-frequency trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms are usually mobile-friendly and available for Windows, Mac, Linux, iOS and Android, making market entry easier and helping with the surge in retail investing.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] The term "trading platform" is generally used to avoid confusion with "trading system".
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] The latter term usually refers to a trading method or strategy rather than the computer system used to execute orders.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] A platform is a type of computing system or operating environment such as a database or other specific software.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Financial transactions were handled manually by brokers or directly by counterparties until the 1970s.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] From then, electronic trading platforms were introduced.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] These platforms and trading venues included electronic communication networks, alternative trading systems and "dark pools".
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] The first electronic trading platforms were typically associated with stock exchanges and allowed brokers to place orders remotely using private dedicated networks and dumb terminals.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Early systems would not always provide live streaming prices and instead allowed brokers or clients to place an order which would be confirmed some time later; these were known as "request for quote" systems.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In 1971, Nasdaq was created by the National Association of Securities Dealers and operated entirely electronically on a computer network.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] It rapidly gained popularity and by 1992, it accounted for 42% of trade volume in the US.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] With the advent of electronic financial markets, electronic trading platforms were also soon launched.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In 1992, Globex became the first electronic trading platform to reach the market.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] E-Trade, a company that started as an online brokerage service, soon also launched its own platform aimed at the consumer.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] These platforms rapidly gained popularity with E-Trade's growth rate at 9% per month in 1999.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In the late 2000s, with the emergence of digital tools, a new generation of investment companies started to appear, which began to offer services to assist non-professional investors in trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In 2007, a multi-asset investment company, eToro, was founded, focusing on copy trading, social trading, and other types of trading services.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] In 2017, the bitcoin exchange Binance was founded.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Trading systems evolved to allow for live streaming prices and near instant execution of orders as well as using the internet as the underlying network meaning that location became much less relevant.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Some electronic trading platforms have built-in scripting tools and even APIs allowing traders to develop automatic or algorithmic trading systems and robots.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] The client graphical user interface of the electronic trading platforms could be used to place various orders and were also sometimes called trading turrets (though this may be a misuse of the term, as some refer to the specialized PBX phones used by traders).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] During the period from 2001 to 2005, the development and proliferation of trading platforms saw the setting up of dedicated online trading portals, which were electronic online venues with a choice of many electronic trading platforms rather than being restricted to one institution's offering.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) promulgated Rule 17a-23, which required any registered automated trading platform to report information, including participants, orders, and trades every quarter.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Requiring platforms to comply with enhanced pre- and post-trade transparency requirements has provided a stronger incentive for users to trust electronic trading platforms.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Market fragmentation led some Nasdaq market makers on Instinet to quote prices that were better than their own quotes on Nasdaq.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] To address this discrepancy, the SEC introduced the Order Handling Rules in 1996.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] These rules required stock exchange specialists and Nasdaq market makers to publicly display any price quoted on a proprietary trading system that represented an improvement of their displayed prices.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Another order handling rule required a market maker to display the size and price of any customer limit order that either increased size at the quoted price or improved the market maker's quotation.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Decimalization was instituted in 2001 by the SEC, requiring market makers to value financial instruments by increments of $0.01 as opposed to the previous standard of $0.0625.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] This change significantly lowered margins, providing an incentive for big dealers to utilize electronic management systems and eventually leading to lowered trading costs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Electronic trading platforms frequently provide historical data, including graphs, to help their customers make trading decisions.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] These diagrams may be expanded to contain a large number of dates and are frequently employed in technical analyses of particular instruments.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] To help consumers make decisions about their contracts, trading platforms frequently include recent news.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Articles on certain businesses may be included, as well as updated ratings provided by independent companies that focus on particular commodities.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] Similar information to what professional traders can access is available to retail traders on different applications due to specialized news.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/electronic-trading-platform] The user's portfolio can be tracked, which is another function that is frequently seen on trading platforms and can have an impact on trades based on a trader's past performance.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The **Financial Information eXchange** (**FIX**) protocol is an electronic communications protocol initiated in 1992 for international real-time exchange of information related to securities transactions and markets.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] With trillions of dollars traded annually on the NASDAQ alone, financial service entities are employing direct market access (DMA) to increase their speed to financial markets.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Managing the delivery of trading applications and keeping latency low increasingly requires an understanding of the FIX protocol.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The FIX protocol specification was originally authored in 1992 by Robert "Bob" Lamoureux and Chris Morstatt to enable electronic communication of equity trading data between Fidelity Investments and Salomon Brothers.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX initially addressed information between broker-dealers and their institutional clients.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] At the time, this information was communicated verbally over the telephone.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Fidelity realized that information from their broker-dealers could be routed to the wrong trader, or simply lost when the parties hung up their phones.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] It wanted such communications to be replaced with machine-readable data which could then be shared among traders, analyzed, acted on and stored.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] For example, broker-dealers call with an indication of interest (IOI) to buy or sell a block of stock.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The FIX initiative created new messages such as the IOI.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX is widely used by both the buy side (institutions) as well as the sell side (brokers/dealers) of the financial markets.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Among its users are mutual funds, investment banks, brokers, stock exchanges and ECNs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX has become the standard electronic protocol for pre-trade communications and trade execution.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Although it is mainly used for equity transactions in the front office area, bond derivatives and FX-transactions are also possible.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] One could say that whereas SWIFT is the standard for back office messaging, FIX is the standard for front office messaging.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] However, today, the membership of FIX Protocol Ltd. is extending FIX into block trade allocation and other phases of the trading process, in every market, for virtually every asset class.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Originally, the FIX standard was monolithic, including application layer semantics, message encoding, and session layer in a single technical specification.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] It remained monolithic through FIX version 4.2.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Thereafter, message encodings and session layer specifications began to be split into separate documents, and ultimately, FIX evolved into a family of related technical standards.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Message encoding, called Presentation Layer in the Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model), is responsible for the wire format of messages.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The original FIX message encoding is known as tagvalue encoding.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Each field consists of a unique numeric tag and a value.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The tag identifies the field semantically.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Therefore, messages are self-describing.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Tagvalue encoding is character-based, using ASCII codes.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] A message is composed of a header, a body, and a trailer.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The message fields are separated by the start of heading (SOH) character (ASCII 0x01).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Up to FIX.4.4, the header contains three fields: 8 (`BeginString`), 9 (`BodyLength`), and 35 (`MsgType`).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] From FIXT.1.1 / FIX.5.0, the header contains five or six fields: 8 (`BeginString`), 9 (`BodyLength`), 35 (`MsgType`), 49 (`SenderCompID`), 56 (`TargetCompID`) and the optional 1128 (`ApplVerID`).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The content of the message body is defined by the message type (35 `MsgType`) in the header.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The trailer contains the last field of the message, 10 (`Checksum`), always expressed as a three-digit number (e.g.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX messages are formed from several fields; each field has a tag value pairing that is separated from the next field by a delimiter SOH (0x01).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The tag is an integer that indicates the meaning of the field.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The value is an array of bytes that hold a specific meaning for the particular tag (e.g. tag 48 is SecurityID, a string that identifies the security; tag 22 is IDSource, an integer that indicates the identifier class being used).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The values may be in plain text or encoded as pure binary (in which case the value is preceded by a length field).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The FIX protocol defines meanings for most tags, but leaves a range of tags reserved for private use between consenting parties.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The FIX protocol also defines sets of fields that make a particular message; within the set of fields, some will be mandatory and others optional.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The ordering of fields within the message is generally unimportant, however repeating groups are preceded by a count and encrypted fields are preceded by their length.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The message is broken into three distinct sections: the head, body and tail.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Fields must remain within the correct section and within each section, the position may be important as fields can act as delimiters that stop one message from running into the next.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The final field in any FIX message is tag 10 (checksum).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] There are two main groups of messages—admin and application.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The admin messages handle the basics of a FIX session.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] They allow for a session to be started and terminated and for recovery of missed messages.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The application messages deal with the sending and receiving of trade-related information such as an order request or information on the current state and subsequent execution of that order.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The body length is the character count starting at tag 35 (included) all the way to tag 10 (excluded), including trailing SOH delimiters.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The checksum of a FIX message is always the last field in the message, with tag `10` and a 3 character value.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] It is given by summing the ASCII value of all characters in the message (except for the checksum field itself), then modulo 256.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] For example, in the message above, the summation of all ASCII values (including the SOH characters with ASCII value 1) results in 4158.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Performing the modulo operation gives the value 62.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Since the checksum is composed of three characters, this results in `10=062`.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIXML is an XML schema for FIX messages.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] It is semantically equivalent to tagvalue encoded messages but takes advantage of XML parser technology.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIXML is commonly used for back-office and clearing applications rather than trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Simple Binary Encoding defines a wire format using primitive data types that are native to computing systems.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Message encoding and decoding is therefore much lower latency than character-based protocols since no translation is needed to put data into a format that computers can use.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Aside from latency advantages, performance is more deterministic because SBE messages are constrained by templates and fixed-length data elements are preferred.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Another consequence is that fields are generally at a fixed position so that message filters and routers do not need to crack an entire message to access key fields.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] SBE was developed by the FIX High Performance Working Group to support high performance trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Tagvalue encoding was deemed no longer fit-for-purpose since it is character based rather than binary and its variable-length fields and messages result in non-deterministic performance.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Unlike tagvalue and FIXML, an SBE message is not self-describing.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Only data is sent on the wire with a minimal header to identify the template that controls a message.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Metadata that describes a message layout is exchanged out-of-band between peers.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX Trading Community publishes an XML schema for SBE message schemas.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] A message schema may contain any number of message templates.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] A template describes the fields that constitute a message.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Additionally, a schema provides a listing of simple and composite data types that may be reused by any number of fields.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] From a practical perspective, assuming a C/C++ implementation, and adjusting for endianness: most non-composite types in the message directly map to the same type in the language.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] For example, 32-bit integer maps to `uint32_t`, fixed strings maps `const char *`, floating point maps to `float` and so on.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] One can generate a C/C++ `struct` from the schema definition.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Then, given a pointer to a message buffer, accessing non-composite fields of the message amount to type-casting it to a pointer to structure and accessing structure members directly.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The session layer is responsible for message exchange including checkpoint recovery mechanisms.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The original FIX session protocol did not have its own name since it was part of a monolithic specification covering application layer semantics and message encoding as well.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] However, starting with FIX version 5.0, the session layer was split off as an independent specification with the introduction of FIXT.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIXT was largely the same as the original unnamed session layer in version 4.x, but it offered one significant innovation--it provided a mechanism to mix FIX application layer versions over a common session version.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Theoretically, FIXT is transport independent.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] However, it is usually employed over Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] It guarantees message delivery in both directions.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Messages sent in each direction carry a message sequence number in the message header.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] If there is a communication fault, a peer may request retransmission of missed messages.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Message delivery is supported even in the event of disconnection and later reestablishment of a session.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIXP was developed by the FIX High Performance Working Group to meet the needs of high performance trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The primary need is for low latency message encoding and decoding and control over message delivery guarantees.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] To provide low latency, binary message encodings are supported both for session layer and application messages.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The actual wire format is abstracted in the FIXP specification, so users may select a FIX encoding of their choice, so long as peers agree on a protocol to use.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Early development has used Simple Binary Encoding.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIXP covers both point-to-point and multicast use cases with common primitives.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Delivery guarantees may be asymmetrical.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] For example, a trader may enter orders over an idempotent flow while executions are returned over a recoverable flow.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] In fast moving markets, the delay inherent in retransmission is often undesirable, resulting in missed opportunities or bad trades.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Below is a diagram of how to FIX messaging looks between Buyside/Customer and Sellside/Supplier.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] The latest version of FIX Protocol implements "Transport Independence" by permitting multiple versions of application messages to be carried over a single version of Transport Independent FIX Session (FIXT.1.1 and higher).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Transport Independence also paves the way for transport protocols such as message queues and web services to be used instead of traditional FIX over TCP.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FIX now supports algorithmic trading by the use of FIX Algorithmic Trading Definition Language FIXatdl.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] In 2005, the FIX Trading Community released FAST protocol which stands for FIX Adapted for Streaming.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] FAST is a binary protocol and is used mostly for sending Multicast market data via UDP connections.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/financial-information-exchange] Further, in 2020, the FIX Trading Community released a new FIX binary encoding, based on Simple Binary Encoding (SBE), meant to complement the existing FAST encoding.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] An **order book** is the list of orders (manual or electronic) that a trading venue (in particular stock exchanges) uses to record the interest of buyers and sellers in a particular financial instrument.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] A matching engine uses the book to determine which orders can be fully or partially executed.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] In securities trading, an order book contains the list of buy orders and the list of sell orders.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] For each entry it must keep among others, some means of identifying the party (even if this identification is obscured, as in a dark pool), the number of securities and the price that the buyer or seller are bidding/asking for the particular security.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] When several orders contain the same price, they are referred to as being on a price level.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] Practically, this means that if a bid comes at that price level, all the sell orders on that price level could potentially fulfill that.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] When the order book is part of a matching engine, orders are matched as the interest of buyers and sellers can be satisfied.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] When there are orders where the bid price is equal or higher than the lowest ask, those orders can be immediately fulfilled and will not be part of the open orders book.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] If this situation remains, due to an error or a condition of the market, the order book is said to be crossed.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] The highest bid and the lowest ask are referred to as the top of the book.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] They are interesting because they signal the prevalent market and the bid and ask price that would be needed to get an order fulfilled.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] The difference between the highest bid and the lowest ask is called the bid–ask spread.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] The book depth refers simply to the number of price levels available at a particular time in the book.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] Sometimes the book is represented to a fixed depth, and orders beyond that depth are ignored or rejected, and in other cases the book can contain unlimited levels.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] In most practical applications, an order book contains bid and offer for one security, contract or good, with a specialist matching orders for the specific item.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] In his work, Jean-François Mertens extends this and constructs an order matching mechanism that works across specialists, where he can cross orders that are not only in terms of bid and offer for a given traded item, but bids and offer can be expressed as a linear function of other traded items.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] The advent of retail trading software in the early 2000s enabled more complex charting options for what was previously numerical data.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] An order book might also refer to a business's list of open, unshipped, customer orders, normally time-phased and valued at actual individual order prices, that may include margin and profitability analysis.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/order-book] The basic principle of the order book as used in financial securities, when used to gauge supply and demand, can also apply to the trade of other goods (for example e-commerce).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Straight-through processing exists in numerous areas of financial services, such as payments processing.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Payments may be non-STP due to various reasons such as missing information, information which is not in a machine "understandable" form (such as name and address rather than a code), or human-readable instructions, e.g.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] "Please credit urgently") or simply falls outside of rules for which the bank allows automatic processing (for example, payments of large value or in exotic currencies).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Traditionally, making payments involves many departments in a bank.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Both initiating a payment to be sent and processing a received payment may take days.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] In the past, payments were initiated through numerous "human-friendly" (also known as paper-based) means, such as a human through a paper order, over the phone, or via fax.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The payment order was input into the bank's payment system, then confirmed by a supervisor.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] This confirmation ensured an accurate match of input versus order before sending the payment.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] When multiple banks, countries or currencies were involved, the process often took several hours.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] When the complexity of the payment was higher, the amount of labor increased and additional human intervention resulted in more risk of errors, longer processing time, and higher costs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] In most cases, banks levy charges for non-STP payments or for manual repairs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Alternatively, banks may not charge on a "per repair" basis, but rather levy heavier fees for correspondents that provide lower quality (lower STP) payments.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] STP was developed for equities trading in the early 1990s by James Karat in London for automated processing in the equity markets.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The process before STP was very antiquated: sales traders would have to fill in a deal ticket, blue for buy and red for sell.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The order was invariably scribbled and mostly unreadable.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Upon receiving the order, the trader would often execute an incorrect investment on the market.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] For example, if the client wished to purchase 100,000 shares, but the trader only executed 10,000, the runner would send out the contract for 1,000.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] In those days, there was a T+10 settlement so any errors were "fixable".
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] However, with the new introduction of T+5, the settlement arena changed, and STP was born.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] To reduce the risk of failed settlement, there could only be one "golden source" of information and that it was the responsibility of the sales trader to be correct as they had the power to correct any discrepancies with the client directly.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The goal of STP is to reduce the time it takes to process a transaction, in order to increase the likelihood that a contract or an agreement is settled on time.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The concept has also been transferred into other sectors including energy (oil, gas) trading and banking, and financial planning.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Currently, the entire trade lifecycle, from initiation to settlement, is a complex labyrinth of manual processes that take several days.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Such processing for equities transactions is commonly referred to as T+2 (trade date plus two days) processing, as it usually takes two business days from the "trade" being executed to the trade being settled.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] This means investors who are selling a security must deliver the certificate within two business days, and investors who are buying securities must send payment within two business days.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] But this process comes with higher risks through the occurrence of unsettled trades.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Market conditions fluctuate, meaning a two-day window brings an inherent risk of unexpected losses that investors may be unable to pay for, or settle, their transactions.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Industry practitioners, particularly in the United States, viewed STP as meaning "same-day" settlement or faster, ideally minutes or even seconds.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] The goal was to minimise settlement risk for the execution of a trade and its settlement and clearing to occur simultaneously.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] However, for this to be achieved, multiple market participants must realize high levels of STP.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] In particular, transaction data would need to be made available on a just-in-time basis, which is a considerably harder goal to achieve for the financial services community than the application of STP alone.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] After all, STP itself is merely an efficient use of computers for transaction processing.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] In the past, STP methods were used to help financial firms move to one-day trade settlement of equity transactions, as well as to meet the global demand resulting from the rapid growth of online trading.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Now the concepts of STP are applied to reduce systemic and operational risk and to improve certainty of settlement and minimize operational costs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] There is often confusion within the trading world between STP and an electronic communication network (ECN).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Although they are similar initiatives, ECN connects orders with those of other traders as well as staff liquidity provides.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] An ECN is also typically a bigger pool of orders than a standard STP.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] When fully implemented, STP is able to provide asset managers, brokers and dealers, custodians, banks and other financial services with benefits including shorter processing cycles, reduced settlement risk, and lower operating costs.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Some industry analysts believe that STP is not an achievable goal in the sense that firms are unlikely to find the cost/benefit to reach 100% automation.
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Instead, they promote the idea of improving levels of internal STP within a firm while encouraging groups of firms to work together to improve the quality of the automation of transaction information between themselves, either bilaterally or as a community of users (external STP).
[src:financial-fix-protocol/straight-through-processing] Other analysts, however, believe that STP will be achieved with the emergence of business process interoperability.
